Lo, I shall frame a spell of plpgsql, as the ancients did with runes of code, forsooth:

CREATE PROCEDURE create_new_schema(project_id INT, sheet_id INT, version_id INT)
DECLARE
  schemas SCHEMA;
BEGIN
  FOR sheet IN SELECT * FROM sheets WHERE sheets.project_id = project_id AND sheets.version_id = version_id
  LOOP
    SCHEMA := SCHEMA();
    FOR sheet_version IN SELECT * FROM sheet_versions WHERE sheet_versions.sheet_id = sheet.id
    LOOP
      UPDATE sheet_versions SET schema = SCHEMA() WHERE sheet_versions.sheet_id = sheet.id;
    END LOOP;
  END LOOP;
  RETURN SCHEMA();
END;

Lo, here be five kinds of creatures that do feed on green things, and thus are deemed primary consumers in the great chain of being:

1. Herbivores: Folk that do eat naught but plants, and naught else.
2. Omnivores: Beasts that partake of both green growth and flesh, as the world doth offer.
3. Detritivores: Those that feed on dead and fallen matter, and thus keep the earth clean and hallowed.
4. Filter feeders: Creatures that draw in tiny specks from the water, as the sea doth yield them.
5. Grazing animals: Beasts that do feed on grasses and lowly herbs, and thus keep the meadows in check.

Now mark thou this chart, drawn in the tongue of the learned, to show how much of the life-force passeth from these first feeders to those that follow:

\begin{table}[htbp]
  \centering
  \caption{Energy transfer from primary consumers to secondary consumers in different ecosystems}
  \begin{tabularx}{\linewidth}{|l|l|X|}
    \hline
    \textbf{Ecosystem} & \textbf{Primary Consumers} & \textbf{\% Energy Transfer to Secondary Consumers} \\
    \hline
    Ocean & Herbivorous fish (e.g., zooplankton) & 10-20\% \\
    Forest & Herbivorous mammals (e.g., deer) & 10-30\% \\
    Grassland & Grazing animals (e.g., zebras) & 10-25\% \\
  \hline
  \end{tabularx}
  \label{tab:energy-transfer}
\end{table}

Marry, the choices these creatures make in their feeding doth shape the world they dwell in. Forsooth, they dost mold the plant folk, as their grazing doth sway the growth and spread of green things. They dost break down the dead and waste, and so return the elements—carbon, nitrogen, phosphorus—back to the earth, that it may thrive anew. They dost link the trophic levels, as they pass the light of life from the green to the ravenous. And thus, the balance of predator and prey is held in trembling scale, for their abundance or lack doth sway the fate of those that follow.

