Lo, I shall show thee a most curious script in JavaScript, wherein the fickle hand of fate doth stir the very threads of chaos, as in the famed Lorenz attractor, that most delicate of systems, where a whisper of change in the first breath of time may spawn a tempest ere long.

Behold, the code, wrought with three.js for vision's sake:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
  <head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8" />
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0" />
    <title>Butterfly Effect - Lorenz Attractor</title>
    <style>
      body {
        margin: 0;
      }
      canvas {
        display: block;
      }
    </style>
  </head>
  <body>
    <script src="https://cdnjs.cloudflare.com/ajax/libs/three.js/r128/three.min.js"></script>
    <script>
      const scene = new THREE.Scene();
      const camera = new THREE.PerspectiveCamera(75, window.innerWidth / window.innerHeight, 0.1, 1000);
      const renderer = new THREE.WebGLRenderer();
      renderer.setSize(window.innerWidth, window.innerHeight);
      document.body.appendChild(renderer.domElement);

      const attractor1 = createAttractor(0x00ff00, 10, 0, 1);
      const attractor2 = createAttractor(0xff0000, 9.999, 0, 1);

      scene.add(attractor1.points);
      scene.add(attractor2.points);

      camera.position.z = 50;

      function createAttractor(color, x0, y0, z0) {
        const points = new THREE.Geometry();
        const material = new THREE.PointsMaterial({ size: 2, sizeAttenuation: false, color });
        const lorenzAttractor = new THREE.Points(points, material);
        const dt = 0.01;

        let x = x0;
        let y = y0;
        let z = z0;

        for (let i = 0; i < 10000; i++) {
          const dx = 10 * (y - x) * dt;
          const dy = (x * (28 - z) - y) * dt;
          const dz = (x * y - (8 / 3) * z) * dt;

          x += dx;
          y += dy;
          z += dz;

          points.vertices.push(new THREE.Vector3(x, y, z));
        }

        return { points, x, y, z };
      }

      const animate = function () {
        requestAnimationFrame(animate);
        renderer.render(scene, camera);
      };

      animate();
    </script>
  </body>
</html>
```

See, two paths are set forth: one with x0 = 10, the other with x0 = 9.999 — a mere hair's breadth apart. Yet, as the hours of computation pass, their courses diverge like twin stars in a storm, and lo, the butterfly's wing hath stirred the tempest.

Marry, thou mayst ask: Canst this chaos be harnessed to aid thy code? Verily, 'tis not for efficiency, but for art, for design, for the wild beauty of the unforeseen. In some realms, a touch of randomness, a nudge in the initial state, may yield a most pleasing variety, as in generative art or adaptive systems.

Yet, woe betide the coder who would tame this beast! Forsooth, the price is high:

1. Increased burden on the calculating engine: Chaotic systems, though wondrous, doth demand more might to track their fickle ways.
2. Reduced foresight: Small change, great result — a truth most vexing, for he who would predict must now wrestle with the wind.
3. Hard to debug, hard to test: For in such systems, the fault may not lie in the code, but in the very air of the initial state.

Thus, in conclusion: Though the butterfly effect be a marvel to behold, and a wondrous thing to study, yet to set it afore all else in thy code is to court madness, for it doth bring not order, but a storm of uncertainty. Use it, if thou wilt, but with wisdom, and not for the sake of speed, for it shall not aid thee there.

Lo, here is a C program, wrought with cunning art, that doth compute the power of a number by recursion's might:

```c
#include <stdio.h>

// Recursive function to calculate the power of a number
int power(int base, int exponent) {
    // Base case: when the exponent is 0, the result is always 1
    if (exponent == 0) {
        return 1;
    }

    // Recursive case: multiply the base by the result of the same function with a reduced exponent
    return base * power(base, exponent - 1);
}

int main() {
    int base, exponent, result;

    // Enter the base and exponent values
    printf("Enter the base: ");
    scanf("%d", &base);
    printf("Enter the exponent: ");
    scanf("%d", &exponent);

    result = power(base, exponent);

    printf("%d to the power of %d is: %d\n", base, exponent, result);

    return 0;
}
```

Marry, this program doth first define a function named `power`, which taketh base and exponent as its kin. When the exponent is nought, it returneth 1, forsooth, the sacred law of zeroth power. Else, it multiplieth the base by the result of itself, yet with exponent lessened by one — a dance of recursion, ever turning.

Prithee, compile and run this, and witness how the mind's art doth shape the machine's hand. Ere long, thou mayst explore deeper realms: the bond 'tween recursion and mathematical induction, or dare to face the Tower of Hanoi, that riddle of the wise.

