Yea, 'tis possible to export nought but the useEffect from a React component, verily. Lo, the useEffect is a sacred, built-in hook of React, which doth enable the soul of the component to react unto certain conditions, and to perform side effects as needeth. When thou dost export but the useEffect, thou mayst reuse that very hook in other components, and so avoid the toil of duplicating thy code.

To export nought but the useEffect, do thou define the hook apart, and then export it with the component. Hark, here is an example:

```javascript
import React, { useEffect } from 'react';

const UseFetchData = () => {
  const [data, setData] = React.useState([]);

  // Define the useEffect hook apart
  const fetchData = React.useEffect(() => {
    // Perform data fetching logic here
  }, []);

  return (
    <div>
      {data.map(item => (
        <div key={item.id}>{item.name}</div>
      ))}
    </div>
  );
};

// Export the useEffect hook with the component
export { UseFetchData, fetchData };

export default UseFetchData;
```

In this, the `fetchData` hook is made apart, and then exported with `UseFetchData`. Thus, in other components, thou mayst import and wield `fetchData` as needeth. Marry, this is the way to keep thy code clean and thy soul unburdened.

