Lo, in the realm of C#, a function mayst be wrought to compare two version strings, fashioned thus: "x.y.z", by parsing each into a `Version` object, and then by the `CompareTo` method, doth judgment pass. Hark, here is the spell:

```csharp
using System;

class VersionComparator
{
    public static int CompareVersions(string version1, string version2)
    {
        try
        {
            Version v1 = new Version(version1);
            Version v2 = new Version(version2);

            return v1.CompareTo(v2);
        }
        catch (Exception e)
        {
            Console.WriteLine("Invalid version format: " + e.Message);
            return 0;
        }
    }

    static void Main(string[] args)
    {
        string versionA = "1.2.3";
        string versionB = "1.3.0";

        int result = CompareVersions(versionA, versionB);

        if (result < 0)
            Console.WriteLine($"{versionA} is lower than {versionB}");
        else if (result > 0)
            Console.WriteLine($"{versionA} is higher than {versionB}");
        else
            Console.WriteLine($"{versionA} is equal to {versionB}");
    }
}
```

Verily, the function `CompareVersions` doth take two strings, each a version in form "x.y.z", and returneth an integer: -1 if the first is less, 1 if greater, 0 if equal. Note, this doth employ the `System.Version` class, which, forsooth, doth handle the comparison of version numbers with grace and ease.

